Chloe adjusted her beanie, tugging it lower to cover the pointed tips of her ears as she shoved onto the crowded MTR train. The metal smells and sweat of strangers made her head ache—a constant reminder she didn’t truly belong here. Outside the window, neon signs blurred past, advertising everything from phone deals to dim sum. She longed for the quiet green of the forests she’d only seen in old books her grandmother left behind.

At school, Mr. Li’s biology class droned on about chloroplasts. Chloe’s fingers absently stroked the edge of her notebook. A tiny, forgotten sprig of mint in the corner of her desk—left over from yesterday’s science experiment—suddenly perked up, its leaves turning a brighter green. She froze, heart pounding. Had anyone seen? Around her, classmates whispered about weekend plans. No one noticed the plant. She exhaled, relieved but lonely. *If only they knew why it happened.*

Lunchtime found her under the school’s lone banyan tree, its aerial roots snaking like ancient fingers. She pulled out her sandwich—a simple egg mayo—and noticed the wilting orchid Ying had brought from home. Gently, Chloe brushed her fingertips against its stem. A faint warmth spread, and by the time Ying returned with her milk tea, the orchid had opened one more petal.

“How do you do that?” Ying whispered, eyes wide. “It was dying this morning!”

Chloe blinked, forcing a smile. “Just lucky, I guess. Maybe I watered it well yesterday?” She hoped the lie sounded natural. Ying shrugged, unconvinced but dropping it, and they ate in companionable silence.

After school, the MTR ride home was torture. Chloe pressed herself against the door, eyes closed, listening for the rhythm of the tracks. Suddenly, a soft mew made her open her eyes. A stray tabby kitten huddled near the exit, its left leg twisted at an odd angle. Pain flared in Chloe’s own chest—she *knew* how to ease it, to whisper healing into the flesh with a touch. But if she reached out, if the kitten’s fur rippled under her palm like moss after rain… someone might see. Instead, she dug into her bag for the last of her fish crackers, placing them softly before the kitten. “Be safe,” she murmured, more to herself than the animal. As the train lurched forward, she thought she saw the kitten lift its head, eyes clearer.

The real test came during the school’s annual hike to Tai Mo Shan. Halfway up, Chloe misstepped on a slick rock. Her ankle twisted sharply—she bit her lip to keep from crying out. *Heal. Now.* Warmth flowed through her joint, the pain dissolving into a faint tingling. She forced herself to limp a few steps, then straightened up, pretending it was nothing. “Just a sprain,” she told Toby, who’d stopped to check on her. He frowned, studying her ankle. “That looked bad. You’re walking fine already.”

Later, as they rested at a viewpoint, Toby fell back, staring at the clouds. “You know,” he said quietly, “my grandma used to say some people hear trees talking. Sound crazy, right?” Chloe’s breath hitched. She opened her mouth to deny it, to laugh it off—but Toby didn’t wait for an answer. He reached into his pocket and placed a small, potted fern on her knee. “For the girl who listens to trees,” he said, his voice rough. “No need to explain. Just… thanks for being you.”

Chloe stared at the fern, its fronds delicate and green. When she touched it, a new leaf unfurled, trembling slightly in the mountain breeze. She didn’t tell Toby her secret. But for the first time in years, hiding didn’t feel so heavy. Maybe, she thought, the city could hold both worlds—if she learned where to look for the light.

